Empirical cdf ( Explain in the Lab )

https://towardsdatascience.com/what-why-and-how-to-read-empirical-cdf-123e2b922480

An empirical cumulative distribution function (CDF) is a non-parametric estimator of the underlying CDF of a random variable.

while a CDF is a hypothetical model of a distribution, the ECDF models empirical (i.e.Â observed) data. To put this another way, the ECDF is the probability distribution you would get if you sampled from your sample, instead of the population.

We used the binomial and normal cumulative distributions, respectively, to calculate probabilities and visualize the distribution. In real life, however, the data we collect or observe does not come from a theoretical distribution. We have to use the data itself to create a cumulative distribution.

Refer: https://www.statisticshowto.com/empirical-distribution-function/

https://data.library.virginia.edu/understanding-empirical-cumulative-distribution-functions/

Plot both ecdf and cdf in the same coordinate system. ( Explain in the Lab )

m = 1000
x2 <- rbinom(m,n,p)

plot.ecdf(x2) #we can directly plot using plot.ecdf

lines(0:n,pbinom(0:n,n,p), col = 2, lwd = 3, type = 's')

Example 1: ( Explain in the Lab )

  1. Define the empirical cdf. (instead of plot.ecdf).

  2. Then plot the difference between true cdf and empirical cdf.

#a.
e.cdf <- ecdf(x2) # empirical cdf

#b. Difference
plot(0:n,pbinom(0:n,n,p) - e.cdf(0:n), lwd = 3)
abline(h = 0)

The difference is very small. This means the estimated values are closer to the theoretical values.

Example 2: ( Explain in the Lab )

Plot the empirical CDF and theoretical CDF against each other.

Why do we check this?

plot(e.cdf(0:n), pbinom(0:n,n,p), lwd = 3)
grid(col = 3)
abline(a=0, b = 1, col = 3, lwd = 3)

The points should lie on a straight line.

This is a way of checking whether a given sample has a hypothetical distribution.

In most of the reasearch we do, we may not know the exact probability distribution. In such case, we can compare the ecdf with the cdfâs of known distributions to see if our data follows a known distribution (Which makes our lives easier :))

3. Negative Binomial Distribution

Example 3a: ( done in class )

An oil company has a p = 0.20 chance of striking oil when drilling a well. What is the probability the company drills 7 wells to strike oil r = 3 times?

If we are drillling 7 wells but strike oil only 3 times , that means our number of failures is 4 until 3 successes. Therefore, we need to find the probability

\[P(X=4)\] x = number of failures. size = target for number of successful trials, Must be strictly positive, need not be integer.

prob = probability of success in each trial. \(0 < prob \le 1\).

r = 3
p = 0.20
n = 7 - r
# exact
#dnbinom(x, size, prob)
dnbinom(x = n, size = r, prob = p)
## [1] 0.049152
# Negative Binomial Cumulative Density

# Vector of x-values
x <- 1:10

y <- pnbinom(x, size = r, prob = p)
y
##  [1] 0.0272000 0.0579200 0.0988800 0.1480320 0.2030822 0.2618025 0.3222005
##  [8] 0.3825985 0.4416543 0.4983478
# Plot a graph
plot(x, y, type = 's')

Letâs try a simulation;

# simulated
mean(rnbinom(n = 10000, size = r, prob = p) == n)
## [1] 0.0534

n = 100
p0 = .05
lambda = n*p0

Make a large binomial sample with these parameters;

x3 <- rbinom(1000,n,p0) #binomial
x4 <- rpois(2000,lambda) #poisson

Plot the ecdf of one on top of the cdf of the other.

plot.ecdf(x3) #binomial
points(0:15, ppois(0:15,lambda), col = 2, lwd = 2)

I can compare the ecdf of x3 with a cdf of a poison(lamda) distribution. The result should be a straight line.

Why?

ecdf.3 <- ecdf(x3) #binomial
plot(ecdf.3(seq(0,15,by = .1)),ppois(seq(0,15,by = .1),lambda), lwd = 2)
abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = 3)

5. Hypergeometric Distribution

The phyper() function allows us to calculate hypergeometric probabilities. The first argument is the set of possible values for which we want the probabilities. Then come the parameters, in the order population size, number of good elements, sample size.

Example 5:

What is the probability of selecting x = 14 red marbles from a sample of k = 20 taken from an urn containing m = 70 red marbles and n = 30 green marbles?

\(dhyper(x = x, m = m, n = n, k = k)\)

m = number of successes in the population n = number of failures in the population x = number of successes in the sample k = the sample size

x = 14 #number of successive draws
m = 70 #total number of successes inside the urn
n = 30 #total number of failures inside the urn
k = 20 #number of draws(trails)

dhyper(x = x, m = m, n = n, k = k)
## [1] 0.2140911

Plotting for different number of success draws

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
options(scipen = 999, digits = 2) # significant digits

density = dhyper(x = 1:20, m = m, n = n, k = k)

data.frame(red = 1:20, density) %>%
  mutate(red14 = ifelse(red == 14, "x = 14", "other")) %>%
ggplot(aes(x = factor(red), y = density, fill = red14)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_text(
    aes(label = round(density,2), y = density + 0.01),
    size = 3,
    vjust = 0
  ) +
  labs(title = "PMF of X = x Red Balls",
       subtitle = "Hypergeometric(k = 20, M = 70, n = 30)",
       x = "Number of red balls (x)",
       y = "Density")

Example 6: Aces in a Five-Card Poker Hand

x = seq(0,4) #possible number of aces
m = 4 # number of success elements in population=ace cards
n = 48  # number of failure elements in population= everything except ace cards
k = 5  # simple random sample size(five-card hand)

phyper(x, m, n, k) #Cummulative probabilities
## [1] 0.66 0.96 1.00 1.00 1.00
dhyper(x, m, n, k)
## [1] 0.658842 0.299474 0.039930 0.001736 0.000018

Those are the chances of all the different possible numbers of aces in a poker hand. They are rather hard to read, so letâs try rounding them.

round(phyper(x, m, n, k), 3)
## [1] 0.66 0.96 1.00 1.00 1.00

The histogram of the distribution can be drawn using Plot.

ace_probs = phyper(x, m, n, k)
ace_dist = dhyper(x, m, n, k)
plot(x,ace_dist, main ='Number of Aces in a 5-Card Hand',type='h')

x
## [1] 0 1 2 3 4

Example 7: Red Cards in a Bridge Hand

The essential features of all bridge games, as of whist, are that four persons play, two against two as partners; a standard 52-card deck of playing cards is dealt out one at a time, clockwise around the table, so that each player holds 13 cards; and the object of play is to win tricks, each trick consisting of one card played by each player.

Here is the distribution of the number of red cards in a bridge hand of 13 cards:

x = seq(0,13) #possible red cards
m = 26 #all red cards
n = 26 #all except red cards(failures)
k = 13 # number of draws

bridge_probs = phyper(x, m, n, k)
bridge_dist = dhyper(x, m, n, k)

plot(bridge_dist, main='Number of Red Cards in a 13-Card Hand',type ='h' )

This one looks rather binomial. And indeed, there is a close relation between the binomial and the hypergeometric distributions.

Conditional Distributions

Example 9: Binomial computations

For \(X \sim B(50, .6)\) find

  1. \(P(X < 18)\)
  2. \(P(X < 18 | X > 12)\)
  3. \(P(X > 12| X < 20)\)

with an exact computation and by simulation.

n = 50
p = .25

#a. This can be found using the cdf but without the equal case
pbinom(17.5,n,p)
## [1] 0.94
#b. 
(pbinom(17.5,n,p) - pbinom(12.5,n,p))/(1-pbinom(12.5,n,p))
## [1] 0.89
#c.

(pbinom(19.5,n,p) - pbinom(12.5,n,p))/pbinom(19.5,n,p)
## [1] 0.48
  1. Find these probabilities with a simulation (approximately).
x <- rbinom(100000,n,p)
x1 <- x[x>12]
x2 <- x[x<20]
mean(x < 18)
## [1] 0.95
mean(x1 < 18)
## [1] 0.89
mean(x2 > 12)
## [1] 0.48

Past Exam Questions

Problem 1: Which of the following statments are true? __________

The following is a graph of the pmf of a Poisson distributed random variable \(X\).

A. For this poisson distribution \(\lambda\) is 6.

B. We donât have enough information to calculate \(\lambda\).

C. \(Y_1 \sim Poisson(\lambda_1)\) and \(Y_2 \sim Poisson(\lambda_2)\) be independent, then sum of two independent Poisson random variables has a Poisson distribution with rate parameter \((\lambda_1 +\lambda_1)\).

D. If n is large and p is small, the distribution of the number of successes in n independent trials is largely determined by the value of the mean \(\mu = np\), according to the Poisson approximation.

Problem 2: Which of the following statments are true? __________

TikTok has about 80 million monthly active users in the United States. Research published in April by the Pew Research Center shows that 48% of U.S. adults between 18-29-years-old use TikTok. It drops to 20% in the 30-49-year-old age group, 14% among 50-64-year-olds, and 4% for those 65 and up.

A. Suppose that a random sample of fifty 18-29-years-old who are using TikTok is selected. This selection of the fifty 18-29-years-old is a poisson experiment.

B. The probability that at least 25 of the fifty 18-29-years-old who are using TikTok is 66%.

C. Suppose that a random sample of thirty 30-49-year-old who are using TikTok is selected. The probability that at least 10 of these thirty 30-49-year-olds using TikTok is 94%.

D. Suppose that a random sample of forty 50-64-year-olds who are using TikTok is selected. Since the sample size is large, we can use the normal approximation to find of proportion of more than 30 of 50-64-year-olds who are using TikTok.

Problem 3: Which of the following statments are true? __________

Using the Spotify API mentioned in the Practical part of the exam, we can get audio features of songs for different musicians. Assuming that there are only 300 musicians belonging to the high Energy category (Energy of a song is a measure from 0.0 to 1.0 and represents a perceptual measure of intensity and activity. Typically, energetic tracks feel fast, loud, and noisy.) and 168 of them are pop music artists and the rest are Jazz musicians.

A. If I randomly extracted 35 songs that belong to this high energy category,the probability that more than 15 of them will belong to pop music artists is 0.978.

B. If I randomly extracted 35 songs that belong to this high energy category,the probability that at least 15 of them will belong to Jazz musicians is 0.985.

C. Now imagine I am randomly picking balls with replacement, from an urn containing red(132) balls and blue(168) balls, the probability of choosing exactly 15 red balls out of the 35 balls I picked, will be 0.134.

D. Now imagine I am randomly picking balls without replacement, from an urn containing red(132) balls and blue(168) balls, the probability of choosing exactly 15 red balls out of the 20 balls I picked, will be 0.516.
